div.span: A 27-year-old female presents to general medical clinic for a routine checkup. She has a genetic disease marked by a mutation in a chloride transporter. She has a history of chronic bronchitis. She has a brother with a similar history of infections as well as infertility.

div.style: text-align: justify;
text-align: justify;
div.span: Which of the following is most likely true regarding a potential vitamin deficiency complication secondary to this patient's chronic illness?
(A) It may result in corneal vascularization
(B) It may be exacerbated by excessive ingestion of raw eggs
(C) It may manifest itself as a prolonged PT
(D) It may result in the triad of confusion, ophthalmoplegia, and ataxia

div.div:
The patient's symptoms and genetic disease characterized by a mutation in a chloride transporter, along with a history of chronic bronchitis and a brother with similar symptoms and infertility, suggest the diagnosis of cystic fibrosis. [...] Given the patient's likelihood of having cystic fibrosis and the associated risk of malabsorbing fat-soluble vitamins due to pancreatic insufficiency, the most likely vitamin deficiency complication would be related to vitamin K deficiency, which affects blood clotting.
Therefore, the answer is (C) It may manifest itself as a prolonged PT.
